SIMPLE: mass
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mass
<hw>Mass</hw> <pr>(m⟦adot⟧s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>masse</ets>, <ets>messe</ets>, AS. <ets>maesse</ets>. LL.
<ets>missa</ets>, from L. <ets>mittere</ets>, <ets>missum</ets>, to
send, dismiss: cf. F. <ets>messe</ets>. In the ancient churches, the
public services at which the catechumens were permitted to be present
were called <ets>missa catechumenorum</ets>, ending with the reading of
the Gospel. Then they were <ets>dismissed</ets> with these words :
⟦ldquo⟧Ite, missa est⟦rdquo⟧ [<it>sc</it>. ecclesia], the congregation
is dismissed. After that the sacrifice proper began. At its close the
same words were said to those who remained. So the word gave the name of
<xex>Mass</xex> to the sacrifice in the Catholic Church. See
<er>Missile</er>, and cf. <er>Christmas</er>, <er>Lammas</er>,
<er>Mess</er> a dish, <er>Missal</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(R. C. Ch.)</fld> <def>The sacrifice in the
sacrament of the Eucharist, or the consecration and oblation of the
host.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>The portions of the Mass usually
set to music, considered as a musical composition; -- namely, the
<part>Kyrie</part>, the <part>Gloria</part>, the <part>Credo</part>, the
<part>Sanctus</part>, and the <part>Agnus Dei</part>, besides sometimes
an <part>Offertory</part> and the <part>Benedictus</part>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Canon of the Mass</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Canon</er>.</cd>
-- <col><b>High Mass</b></col>, <cd>Mass with incense, music, the
assistance of a deacon, subdeacon, etc.</cd> -- <col><b>Low
Mass</b></col>, <cd>Mass which is said by the priest throughout, without
music.</cd> -- <col><b>Mass bell</b></col>, <cd>the sanctus bell. See
<er>Sanctus</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mass book</b></col>, <cd>the missal or
Roman Catholic service book.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mass</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mass
<hw>Mass</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Massed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Massing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To celebrate Mass.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Hooker.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mass</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Mass
<hw>Mass</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>masse</ets>, F.
<ets>masse</ets>, L. <ets>massa</ets>; akin to Gr. <?/ a barley cake,
fr. <?/ to knead. Cf. <er>Macerate</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A quantity of matter cohering together so as to make
one body, or an aggregation of particles or things which collectively
make one body or quantity, usually of considerable size; <as>as, a
<ex>mass</ex> of ore, metal, sand, or water</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If it were not for these principles, the bodies of the earth,
planets, comets, sun, and all things in them, would grow cold and
freeze, and become inactive <qex>masses</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir I.
Newton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A deep <qex>mass</qex> of continual sea is slower stirred⟦br⟧
To rage.</q> <rj><qau>Savile.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Phar.)</fld> <def>A medicinal substance made into a
cohesive, homogeneous lump, of consistency suitable for making pills;
<as>as, blue <ex>mass</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A large quantity; a sum.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All the <qex>mass</qex> of gold that comes into Spain.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir W. Raleigh.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He had spent a huge <qex>mass</qex> of treasure.</q> <rj><qau>Sir
J. Davies.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Bulk; magnitude; body; size.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This army of such <qex>mass</qex> and charge.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The principal part; the main body.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Night closed upon the pursuit, and aided the <qex>mass</qex> of
the fugitives in their escape.</q> <rj><qau>Jowett
(Thucyd.).</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Physics)</fld> <def>The quantity of matter which a
body contains, irrespective of its bulk or volume.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Mass</xex> and <xex>weight</xex> are often used, in
a general way, as interchangeable terms, since the <xex>weight</xex> of
a body is proportional to its <xex>mass</xex> (under the same or equal
gravitative forces), and the <xex>mass</xex> is usually ascertained from
the <xex>weight</xex>. Yet the two ideas, <xex>mass</xex> and
<xex>weight</xex>, are quite distinct. <xex>Mass</xex> is the quantity
of matter in a body; <xex>weight</xex> is the comparative force with
which it tends towards the center of the earth. A <xex>mass</xex> of
sugar and a <xex>mass</xex> of lead are assumed to be equal when they
show an equal <xex>weight</xex> by balancing each other in the
scales.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Blue mass</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Blue</er>.</cd> --
<col><b>Mass center</b></col> <fld>(Geom.)</fld>, <cd>the center of
gravity of a triangle.</cd> -- <col><b>Mass copper</b></col>, <cd>native
copper in a large mass.</cd> -- <col><b>Mass meeting</b></col>, <cd>a
large or general assembly of people, usually a meeting having some
relation to politics.</cd> -- <col><b>The masses</b></col>, <cd>the
great body of the people, as contrasted with the higher classes; the
populace.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mass</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Mass
<hw>Mass</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To form or collect into a mass; to
form into a collective body; to bring together into masses; to
assemble.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But <qex>mass</qex> them together and they are terrible
indeed.</q> <rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Massacre</ent>⟦br⟧

